<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow erratic as Europe holds
sway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCKS moved erratically in a narrow trading range yesterday as Wall
Street tried to absorb the bewildering events in European money markets,
writes Martin Dickson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at 3,319.21, down 8.11, after
retreating in the late afternoon from a minor gain. Trading volume on the
New York Stock Exchange was an active 231.6m shares. The Standard &amp; Poor's
500 index ended a slight 0.15 up at 419.92 and the Nasdaq composite was
finally 1.97 off at 585.89.
The blue chip Dow index declined some 16 points in reaction to the Bank of
England's interest rate rise, but then began to rally as rumours swept New
York that the Bundesbank would move quickly to cut German interest rates. US
equities reversed direction again when Britain suspended its currency from
the European exchange rate mechanism and hopes of a German rate cut faded.
A further domestic damper on the market was the US industrial production
figures for August, showing a seasonally adjusted fall of 0.5 per cent,
compared to a consensus forecast of a 0.3 per cent decline.
International Business Machines fell Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 82 7/8 in
active trading after several more analysts lowered their ratings on the
stock and cut back their earnings forecasts. The move followed news late on
Monday that another manufacturer of mainframe computers, Amdahl, was
expecting a third-quarter loss because of poor market demand.
Federal Express, which reported a sharp fall in first-quarter net income
after the market closed on Tuesday, dropped Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 36 7/8
. Yesterday several analysts lowered their earnings forecasts for the group
and at least one downgraded the stock.
In the energy sector, Exxon rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 63 1/4 . Atlantic
Richfield moved ahead Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 119 3/4 as an analyst raised
his forecast for the company's third-quarter earnings, citing firm crude
prices. Occidental Petroleum eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 18 5/8 after an
analyst's downgrading of the stock due to chemical market conditions.
Polaroid was unchanged at Dollars 32 3/4 in spite of news that the company
had unveiled a new compact, autofocus instant camera.
General Dynamics gained Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 79 1/4 after a meeting with
analysts on Tuesday at which the defence company produced evidence that its
efforts to improve efficiency were bearing fruit. Several analysts yesterday
lifted their 1992 and 1993 earnings forecasts for the group.
Canada
TORONTO closed near the day's low as uncertainty surrounding European
currencies and interest rates depressed bank shares, but the overall market
was only moderately down. The same uncertainties boosted gold shares, the
sector's index advancing 183.2 to 5,660.3.
The TSE 300 index finished 10.3 off at 3,453.8 and falls outscored rises by
318 to 247 after volume of 39.6m shares.
Among golds, American Barrick climbed CDollars 1 1/4 to CDollars 39 7/8 ,
Echo Bay CDollars  1/2 to CDollars 8 3/8 and Placer Dome CDollars 5/8 to
CDollars 13 1/2.
