<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / SIB replies to City critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and Investments Board, the city's chief watchdog, yesterday
replied to critics who have accused it of dragging its feet over the
creation of a new regulatory body for retail financial services.
Ms Colette Bowe, director of retail markets at the SIB, said the body had no
power under the rules of the Financial Services Act to force firms into a
new proposed regulatory body to be known as the Private Investment
Authority, even if it wanted to.
Speaking at a Financial Times conference on retail investment regulation, Ms
Bowe defended the SIB's failure to take a hard line with the banks and
building societies whose financial services arms it regulates directly.
Those firms are under pressure from others within in the industry to join
the new body so that competing firms in the same business are regulated by
the PIA.
Ms Bowe also defended the SIB's new proposed disclosure regime for life
insurance products, which has been criticised by consumer groups and the
financial press for going too far to meet the concerns of the life insurance
industry.
She said: 'We believe very strongly in holding a dialogue with the industry
and with consumers as we frame regulation . . . For regulators not to do
this would lead us towards inflexible, onerous and finally unworkable
regulation.'
However, Mr Tom King, general manager of marketing at Standard Life
Assurance, said that in spite of criticisms levelled at the new regime by
consumer groups, it was still detrimental to the life industry.
'I believe that the bases that we now have to use to disclose expenses will
unfairly affect the sales of life policies.
'Many clients will not look past the costs to see the benefits - to their
own detriment,' he said.
Meanwhile, at the same conference, Mr Keith Bedell-Pearce, chief executive
of Prudential Financial Services, said the life insurance industry would be
reluctant to support the Investors Compensation Scheme to the extent that it
has, unless banks and building societies joined the PIA, too.
</TEXT>
