<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: Secretive body debates next step
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE EC monetary committee, which was summoned to a crisis meeting in
Brussels last night after sterling's suspension in the Exchange Rate
Mechanism, is a highly secretive body.
Senior European Commission and national officials in Brussels at first even
refused to confirm that the meeting would take place, let alone where. The
meeting began at the Borschette conference centre towards midnight, with
some officials indicating it could continue well into the morning.
Mr Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor of the exchequer, called the meeting in
his capacity as current president of the EC finance ministers' council.
The monetary committee groups senior EC treasury and central bank officials,
as well as their European Commission counterparts. It is chaired at present
by Mr Jean-Claude Trichet, the French treasury director. Britain is
represented by Sir Nigel Wicks, second permanent secretary at the treasury
with responsibility for international monetary affairs.
The 26-strong committee lies at the heart of EC economic and monetary
policy. In effect, it manages the ERM. It was the monetary committee that
issued the communique last weekend on the devaluation of the lira and the
cut in German interest rates.
The committee also has a strong interest in the intricacies of the
Maastricht Treaty on European union.
</TEXT>
