<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / EC officials hold emergency talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community finance officials were locked in emergency talks in
Brussels early today following the suspension yesterday of sterling's
membership of the European exchange rate mechanism.
The UK government's move to withdraw sterling 'temporarily' from the ERM
followed the largest assault by currency speculators on the exchange rate
system since its formation in 1979.
Sterling fell sharply against all leading currencies. In New York, it lost 5
per cent against the dollar from Tuesday's London close, and fell to
DM2.6951, against its former ERM floor of DM2.7780. Very slow dealings early
in Tokyo, as traders awaited the outcome of the Brussels meeting, saw the
pound at DM2.6850.
On the agenda at the Brussels meeting of the EC's monetary committee was
expected to be the temporary withdrawal from the mechanism of its other
weaker currencies - the Italian lira, the Spanish peseta and perhaps the
Portuguese escudo - all of which were said by foreign exchange dealers
overnight to be trading below their ERM floor levels.
The move followed a day of deep confusion on European foreign exchanges,
which ended with the UK government rescinding the second of two interest
rate rises announced during the day.
The confusion came after foreign exchange traders in Europe seized on the
uncertainty surrounding next Sunday's French referendum on the Maastricht
treaty to increase speculation about an imminent realignment of currencies
within the exchange rate mechanism.
The meeting of the EC monetary committee - which has powers to decide on
currency realignments - had been called following intense talks among senior
economic policy makers in European capitals after the failure of central
banks' intervention to support the weaker EMS currencies.
Rises at one stage totalling 5 percentage points in UK interest rates and
huge purchases of sterling by the Bank of England failed to lift the pound
above its permitted ERM floor against the D-Mark.
Heavy intervention elsewhere in Europe also failed to alleviate renewed
pressure on the Italian lira - which had been devalued by 7 per cent at the
weekend - and on the Spanish peseta.
In London, overnight money market rates spiked to 100 per cent, while the
one-month rate neared 30 per cent. Stocks, however, rallied on hopes of an
imminent devaluation of sterling and prospects for German interest rate
cuts.
</TEXT>
