<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / Industry's leaders react with dismay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Industrial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING UK industrialists reacted with dismay yesterday to the rise in
interest rates before the announcement last night that the second increase
would not take place.
They also expressed fears that this would deal a further blow to consumer
demand and deepen the recession.
Most reluctantly accepted, however, that the government had little choice
but to act as it did and supported its efforts to defend sterling's parity
within the European exchange rate mechanism.
'We need 15 per cent interest rates like we need a hole in the head,' said
Sir Michael Angus, president of the Confederation of British Industry. 'But
if it is a choice between that and devaluation, then I suppose it will have
to be.'
Nonetheless, some businessmen feared the pressure on sterling could make
devaluation inevitable. A minority, led by Sir Owen Green, chairman of BTR,
the industrial conglomerate, argued that sterling should be taken out of the
ERM entirely.
'These are war conditions. We have to know what we are fighting for. Is it a
British pound or a D-Mark pound?' Sir Owen said. 'If we start to devalue,
all the precedents say we don't know what the rate should be. If we float,
we know what the real value is for the British pound and call up the
troops.'
For most businesses, however, the most pressing concern was the outlook for
demand. Some industry spokesmen argued that, almost regardless of what
happened next, yesterday's events had inflicted a devastating blow to
consumer demand.
'People will no longer be buying as of now. They will be stopped in their
tracks,' said Mr Neil Marshall, economist at the Retail Motor Industry
Federation. He warned of another round of business bankruptcies.
Others said much depended on how long interest rates remained at crisis
levels, and whether they passed through to mortgage rates. Several believed
that it would be politically and economically impossible for the government
to hold current interest rates for more than a few weeks.
Several companies yesterday called on the government to take steps to revive
the economy.
</TEXT>
