<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: Swedish marginal lending rate hits
500%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RIKSBANK, Sweden's central bank, raised its marginal lending rate to a
staggering 500 per cent yesterday, the highest level ever, in an effort to
crush rumours of a devaluation in the Swedish krona and reverse the huge
outflow of capital seen earlier this week.
Mr Carl Bildt, the prime minister who heads a minority centre-right
government, summoned leaders of all the main political parties to a meeting
yesterday evening in an attempt to win support for proposed cuts in
government spending and restore some calm to the markets.
The government said it was supporting the Riksbank's measures to defend the
krona, (which is linked to the Ecu), and said a devaluation of the currency
was out of the question, given Sweden's commitment to a fixed exchange rate.
Following Britain's decision last night to suspend sterling's membership of
the Exchange Rate Mechanism, economists in Sweden warned that the krona
would probably continue to come under pressure today.
Dealers estimated that 'tens of billions of kronor' flooded out of Sweden on
Tuesday and yesterday morning.
At 8.30am, the Riksbank raised its marginal rate from 20 per cent to 75 per
cent, but this was insufficient to reverse the outflow and it was forced to
raise the rate again at 3.30pm, to 500 per cent.
Mr Bengt Dennis, Riksbank governor, said the move had the desired effect of
drawing back capital in the last half-hour of trading.
He said that the marginal rate would remain at a high level for 'days rather
than weeks' in order to support the krona.
The Riksbank's marginal rate applies to only the top tranche of the banking
system's borrowings from the central bank. The marginal rate of 500 per cent
affects just the top SKr2.2bn (Pounds 214m) slice of total bank borrowings,
which currently amount to SKr68.2bn.
As a result, the average borrowing cost for the Swedish banking system has
risen to 38 per cent, compared with about 24 per cent when the marginal rate
was 75 per cent last Wednesday.
Swedish interest rates have see-sawed over the last week. as domestic
political worries coincided with turmoil in the international markets. The
Riksbank raised its marginal interest rate to 75 per cent from 24 per cent
on September 9 in order to defend the krona after Finland's decision to stop
linking the markka to the Ecu. Sweden lowered the rate on Monday to 20 per
cent, after the Bundesbank's decision to cut German interest rates.
Swedish short-term interest rates shot up yesterday, with the yield on
three-month treasury bills closing at 35 per cent, compared with 25 per cent
at the previous day's close.
Yields on six-month bills climbed from 22 per cent to 30 per cent.
Longer-dated government paper underwent a slight fall in yields with
five-year bonds ending at 12.30 per cent, compared with 12.58 per cent the
previous day.
Mortgage rates have risen in response, putting pressure on some households,
although many homeowners in Sweden have fixed-rate mortgages.
</TEXT>
