<DATE>920917
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / The Lex Column: Builders/property
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Hard as the blow finally fell, the stock market was at least partly braced
for a sudden interest rate rise. Those investors who were betting that the
move hastened a sterling devaluation - and who were tentatively buying
building stocks yesterday on the back of it - might ponder the dazed state
of most homeowners and prospective housebuyers as they digested the news
last night. Confidence in the housing market was already fragile. Unless
interest policy is wholly reversed, housing transactions in the next six
months could completely dry up.
If the blow to confidence has made the short-term outlook even bleaker than
before, there can be no guarantee that a different exchange rate policy
would offer sure relief in the medium term. There remains a structural
problem in the property market. On the demand side, individuals and
companies are weighed down by debts accumulated in the heady days of asset
inflation in the late 1980s. On the supply side, house repossessions may be
flattening out, but the number of building society customers in arrears of
more than six and 12 months has been rising ominously.
Much the same sort of shadow overhangs the commercial property market, where
hopes are no doubt pinned on a resurgence of inflation. Property was much in
vogue as a hedge in the second half of the 1970s, but it is worth
remembering that in those days UK investors were shackled by exchange
controls and there was nowhere else to go.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-2593</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIQC8AFOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920917
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / The Lex Column: Day of reckoning
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In the long months of struggle to maintain sterling's parity within the ERM,
it has become fashionable to see fixed rate bonds as a more attractive
investment than equities. The chancellor's decision to suspend ERM
membership means that question must now be re-addressed. Whatever
arrangements are finally made for sterling in its relationship with other
European currencies, the credibility of a policy designed to eradicate
inflation has been undermined. Had the government chosen a lower central
rate, or else to follow the Bundesbank in raising interest rates last
December, its ERM adventure might not have come to quite such a sticky end.
As it is, yesterday's 2 point rise in base rates was too late to establish
credibility. Not only is the policy now revealed as questionable; its
implementation was also cack-handed.
This is not to say, however, that inflation will immediately return with a
vengeance. Demand is so subdued and consumers have been so badly burned by
the great deflation that it is hard to see price pressures reasserting
themselves very quickly. Besides, much depends on how long base rates are
held at 12 per cent. To be sure, sterling is already some 10 per cent below
its peak against the dollar. There should be some economic stimulus from
that. But it will take much lower interest rates to restore confidence to
the housing market.
The equity market was thus right to dismiss yesterday's attempt to raise
base rates to 15 per cent as untenable unless the government was determined
to engineer a slump. Maybe the market is now at the turning point. In that
case investors must also address relative values, a process which will
favour cyclical stocks rather than defensive ones like utilities and
pharmaceuticals. Still, caution is called for. The ingredients for growth
are not yet in place and it is not clear how policy will settle down. The
government may hope to salvage some anti-inflation credibility by climbing
back aboard a reconstituted - though certainly weaker - ERM. Another
interest cut by Germany would help. But before Sunday's Maastricht vote in
France, there is no telling whether re-entry will be possible, or at what
exchange or interest rate.
What is clear is that there is little point in floating freely outside the
ERM and in keeping interest rates high in an attempt to track the system.
Sweden has shown the cost of life in the twilight zone. If there is any
logic in floating free, it must be to set interest rates at a level that
reflects the state of the economy and allows the exchange rate to find its
own, much lower level. Were that the government's ultimate plan, equities
would be an outstanding buy.
By the end of next year, however, inflation could then be more like 5 per
cent than 2. The gilts market could not ignore that, even though there are
some consoling factors. The premium over German government bonds has already
moved out to 200 basis points compared with around 120 after the election.
Yesterday's heavy intervention will reduce immediate funding needs. If
sterling were allowed to stabilise at a significantly lower level, foreign
buyers might not demand a much greater increase in the premium over German
paper. Even a large PSBR could then be quite easily funded.
That said, it is now no longer plausible to expect gilt yields to converge
with those in Germany. The attractions that seemed so real in April have
grown elusive. Equities have not quite regained their former glory, but
watch this space.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 26
</PAGE>
