<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / Labour attacks retailers on cards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE retailers were accused yesterday of charging 'astronomic' rates of
interest on their store cards by the Labour party after a survey showed that
many high-street retail chains charge an average of 30 per cent a year
interest on their store cards.
For the first time, Labour has called on the government to ask the Office of
Fair Trading to investigate store cards.
The survey shows that several well-known high street chains, including John
Lewis, Burton, Habitat, and Next, have not cut interest charges on their
store cards in the past two years even though base rates had fallen from 15
per cent to 10 per cent before yesterday's increase.
Mr Robin Cook, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, described store-card
interest rates as a scandal. 'Some of these stores must be making more out
of their astronomic interest rates than they are making out of retailing,'
Mr Cook said.
'There is no point in the big stores' complaining about the lack of consumer
confidence if they are not prepared to help. Customers can hardly be
expected to take on more credit at these rates of usury,' he continued.
</TEXT>
