<DATE>920917
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 92 / Lobby on performance pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of large British companies led by Wellcome, the pharmaceutical
company, is to lobby urgently for changes in legislation on profit-related
pay after a sudden reversal of Inland Revenue practice last month.
In an unexpected statement in July, the Revenue issued a statement of
practice that disqualified from tax relief profit-related pay schemes using
certain formulae that it had previously allowed.
Mr Neville Machin, Wellcome's group employee relations manager, expressed
frustration that the Revenue's plans will bar its scheme, which it has drawn
up after several years' negotiations with the Revenue.
Wellcome had used a formula to calculate its scheme, which was geared to
rewarding improved rather than static performance.
Although tax relief for the current year is not affected, the scheme will in
future be disqualified.
Employees in approved schemes can receive the lower of Pounds 4,000 or 20
per cent of their salary tax-free.
The number of approved schemes more than doubled from 1,277 to 2,597 in the
year to March 1992. The number of employees covered rose from 350,100 to
718,069 during the period.
'If you read between the lines, what happened is the Revenue's advisers said
that the schemes they had been approving did not conform to the
legislation,' Mr Machin said.
'You should not be using fiscal stimuli to reward static performance. If you
make Pounds 100m and have agreed 5 per cent profit-related pay, then make
Pounds 100m the next year, you have gone backwards,' he said.
Wives can now apply to the Inland Revenue to receive all or half of the
married couple's allowance, after changes announced in the budget earlier
this year.
The Revenue has issued a new document - Form 18 - which should be completed
before April 6 next year, when the new system begins.
Under the new arrangement, the wife is eligible to receive half - or, with
the consent of her husband, all - of the basic Pounds 1,720 allowance.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
