<TEXT>
DOMINION Mining, one of a crop of emerging Australian gold producers, has
overcome lower gold prices to make a strong return to the black in the year
to June.
The directors yesterday reported that the company had turned net losses of
ADollars 26.7m (USDollars 19.54m) into ADollars 18.1m profits on a 6.6 per
cent rise in sales to ADollars 265.8m from ADollars 249.2m. The previous
year was affected by an ADollars 81.3m abnormal loss.
The annual dividend has been reduced to 4 cents a share from 4.5 cents.
The directors warned that an accent on cost reduction would lead to a small
fall in gold production in the current year.
Gold output rose to 436,605oz from 388,021oz but the average price received
fell to ADollars 598 per oz from ADollars 626.
The directors said the cost of production was running at ADollars 376 per
oz.
'A strong forward sales position has been maintained, with over 900,000oz
forward sold at an average deliverable price of ADollars 580 per oz,' they
said.
'The group net operating cash flow for the financial period was ADollars
81.8m. Total equivalent cash increased to ADollars 46.8m and the group
re-mained totally debt free.
'The strong cash flow and debt free status enables the company to examine
acquisition opportunities.
'The company will continue to review expansion options from its own resource
port-folio, search for sound ac-quisitions and above all maintain the
aggressive and innovative exploration programme.'
The tax provision was ADollars 11.4m compared with a ADollars 17.1m credit,
and depreciation took ADollars 45.5m against ADollars 42.4m.
