<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / The Liberal Democrats At Harrogate: Steel urges broader
powers for UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEVELOPING the United Nations as a supranational authority able to intervene
in countries' internal affairs was the way to tackle the global problems
that had arisen since the end of the Cold War, Sir David Steel, the party's
former leader, said yesterday, Alison Smith writes.
Had the party's proposal for a permanent UN peacekeeping force been adopted,
he said, the organisation could have been more effective in its efforts in
the former Yugoslavia.
'We need less firefighting and more fire prevention,' he said, referring to
yesterday's announcement of an additional troop deployment for Bosnia.
Sir David said the UN should be able to levy richer nations to put resources
into achieving a sustainable environment. It should also be able to
intervene in governments' affairs when it found brutality and gross
violations of the human rights of minorities.
Sir David said: 'International statesmen must come to their senses and
recognise that our only hope is to use all our expertise in new technology
and communications to create a healthier world, for it is now a practical
possibility to achieve that - given the necessary political will.'
He contrasted the Liberal Democrats' readiness to consider such
international moves with 'the parochialism of both Labour and the Tories'.
He accused Mr John Major of relinquishing his responsibilities as leader of
the EC council of ministers in refusing to take part in a French television
debate on the Maastricht treaty.
</TEXT>
