<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / The Liberal Democrats At Harrogate: Local co-operation to
oust Tories proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CO-OPERATION at local level between Labour and Liberal Democrats was
envisaged as the way forward for the centre-left by two MPs yesterday.
But, as the Liberal Democrats prepared to debate party strategy today, there
were clear signs that they were still deeply divided.
The conference organisers have devised a 'purist' amendment effectively
ruling out formal dialogue on electoral pacts with any other party. The
party leadership last night made clear it would oppose the amendment.
At a packed fringe meeting Mr Frank Field, Labour MP for Birkenhead, and Sir
David Steel, former Liberal Democrat leader, discussed how much the parties
had in common and spoke of using local agreements between the parties to
defeat the Conservatives.
If Labour came to its senses it would realise that there was little point in
forcing constituency Labour parties to put up candidates in Tory-Lib Dem
marginals, Sir David said.
He was unrepentant about the fact that such an arrangement would be a
'one-way bargain' and said that the prize for Labour would be the greater
chance of the creation of an anti-Tory majority in the House of Commons.
'Without that, we will always be caricatured as the patsies who are going to
put Labour into government, and that doesn't do us any good.'
Mr Field highlighted the difference in attitude between Liberal Democrat
voters and party activists.
He said that formal pacts would not work because about half Liberal Democrat
voters disliked Labour more than the Tories, but said that as a joint agenda
developed co-operation would emerge 'because Labour activists and Liberal
Democrat activists believe they have some genuine common purpose to achieve
by defeating the incumbent Tory'.
Lord Jenkins of Hillhead, the first president of the former Social
Democratic party, also called for co-operation between parties. If the past
three elections showed anything, he said, 'they show that neither the
Liberal Democrats nor Labour can beat the Conservatives on their own.'
Co-operation on individual policy issues such as freedom of information
where the parties agreed was put forward at another meeting by Ms Mo Mowlam,
a member of Labour's shadow cabinet.
She called for an end to the 'farce' of opposition 'where absolutely
everything they do is silly and everything we do is right.' The Labour
leadership has maintained an official silence on the question of pacts but
is said to be sympathetic to Ms Mowlam's approach.
</TEXT>
