<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / The Liberal Democrats At Harrogate: Kennedy looks beyond
pacts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR CHARLES Kennedy, president of the Liberal Democrats, yesterday urged
party activists to cut through theoretical debates about deals with the
Labour party and instead confront the threat of permanent Conservative
entrenchment in government.
Mr Kennedy sought to defuse the tensions which have built up among delegates
over the potential for pacts with Mr John Smith, the Labour leader.
He called on Liberal Democrats to devote their energies to building an
'intellectual framework which challenges the Tories' appeal to
self-interest, but not in the same patronising or paternalistic way'.
Mr Kennedy, who favours keeping open the door to co-operation with Labour at
some stage in the present parliament, said that the task for the party in
Harrogate was 'not to try and tie our feet in ribbons about hypothetical,
undeliverable political pacts'.
It had instead to consider whether the first-past-the-post electoral system,
reinforced by demographic trends and prospective changes in constituency
boundaries, pointed to an era of 'entrenched Conservative hegemony'.
Against that background the Liberal Democrats should seek to become a
'catalyst' for reform in British politics.
The party should focus its efforts now on honing a distinctive political
appeal which recognised 'the primacy of the individual within the context of
a community of shared values'.
It should appeal to the individual drive for self-improvement but also
explain the need for shared values.
Mr Kennedy also underlined the concern among the party's leadership that a
conference debate which is scheduled for today on the Liberal Democrats'
future electoral strategy should not close the door to co-operation with
other opposition parties.
Stressing the potential which existed to reshape the opposition to the
Conservative government, he concluded that as a catalyst for such a process
the party could - as in the chemical process - change the political
landscape without losing its basic form, properties or identity.
</TEXT>
