<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / City looks to defend markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING City institutions were yesterday considering making a forthright
statement in defence of unrestricted foreign exchange markets, because of
concerns that the markets and dealers are being blamed for the inability of
the UK government to reduce interest rates.
The Bank of England has been approached to join the Corporation of London
and leading banks in making a public statement that unrestricted flows of
capital in foreign exchange markets are positive for the economy.
'Politicians are representing the free markets as a bad thing', said an
executive involved in the discussions. 'We fear that the general public
blames the City for the country's economic problems.' The mood among City
dealers and executives over the past few weeks of sharp fluctuations in
currency markets - prompting huge rises in interest rates in Italy and
Sweden - has become very defensive.
There are widespread fears that the exchange volatility and the government's
inability to cut interest rates could lead to pressure for new regulations
to be introduced into foreign exchange markets.
City institutions want to make it clear it is not their fault that sterling
is under pressure. However, they are unclear how to say this without by
implication blaming the government, which they are reluctant to do.
The Bank of England has not decided whether it will get involved in making
any such defence of free markets.
City institutions are also organising a related campaign to reassert the
strength of Europe's financial markets. They fear that international
financial institutions may reduce their investments in Europe if the French
vote against the Maastricht agreement on Sunday.
The Corporation of London and UK banks want to stress the City will stay one
of the world's three most important financial centres, whatever the vote.
</TEXT>
