<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Deadlock in French prisons strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government yesterday offered to freeze the temporary suspension
of 40 prison officers announced on Monday as a conciliatory gesture towards
resolving their industrial dispute. However, its efforts were blocked when
two of the biggest officers' unions, the UFAP and Force Ouvriere, refused to
attend a morning negotiating meeting.
Despite the government's efforts, staff at most of France's 182 jails stayed
out on strike yesterday. There were ugly scenes as riot police tried to
restore order, sometimes clashing with picketing officers as well as
inmates. The strike, which follows after a similar stoppage last month, was
sparked by last Friday's murder of a warder at Clairvaux prison, when seven
inmates tried to shoot their way out of the jail.
Squads of security vans arrived at Clairvaux throughout the morning to move
100 of its 220 inmates. Clairvaux is one of France's maximum security
prisons, but staff have refused to return to work until the prison has been
thoroughly searched after Friday's shooting.
Warders at Baumettes have also demanded that their jail be searched before
they return to work. The warden's death was the latest in a series of
violent incidents, which have included attacks on staff and dramatic
helicopter snatches of inmates from prison roofs.
The prison officers are demanding more staff and improved facilities,
including the reintroduction of the top security wings recently phased out
by France's Socialist government. The justice ministry has promised to
review the whole prison system and to table legislation to improve financial
compensation for officers' dependents.
The French airline pilots' unions have called out their members on a 24-hour
strike today in protest at proposed changes to their working arrangements.
The pilots' union criticised the European Commission by claiming that it was
tabling changes which would involve more flying hours and shorter rest
periods for French pilots.
</TEXT>
