<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Russia risks UN clash over Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council's post cold war unity appeared at risk last night
over the issue of former Yugoslavia's continued membership in the general
assembly.
Under the rules, the 15-member council may recommend to the larger body the
exclusion of a member state and the western powers have signalled their wish
to follow that course in the Yugoslav case.
But Russia is adamantly opposed to any move that would adversely affect the
Belgrade government's UN rights - raising the possibility that a western
resolution to this effect might be vetoed. This would be a rare event in the
changed political climate in the security council.
A new session of the general assembly, the 47th, opened yesterday and the
credentials of what now is called 'the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
(Serbia and Montenegro)' could be challenged by a committee set up routinely
to examine the credentials of all of the member states. It was a similar
committee's recommendation that brought about the exclusion of South Africa
from the general assembly in 1974.
South Africa remains a UN member but cannot participate in most UN work.
While the EC foreign ministers, meeting in London last weekend, agreed to
try to block the Belgrade government's claim to be the automatic UN
successor to the former Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, a founding
member, several Moslem states also backed the effort.
Russian objections are somewhat ironic given the fact that Moscow managed to
retain its permanent security council seat last December following the
Soviet break-up.
Mr Yuli Vorontsov, then the Soviet ambassador and now the UN representative
of the Russian Federation, was the council president at the time and was
widely credited with diplomatic sleight of hand.
Although a draft paper being circulated by Britain, France and Belgium, with
US and Austrian support, would recommend that the general assembly deny
Belgrade's claim to continue automatically former Yugoslavia's membership,
and exclude its participation in the work of UN bodies, some western
diplomats questioned last night whether the issue would be pressed to a
vote.
See Editorial Comment
</TEXT>
