<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equities slide on interest rate fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE OPTIMISM kindled in the UK stock market by the reductions in German
interest rates was quashed yesterday by sterling's fall to within a hair's
breadth of its permitted ERM low, which brought renewed fears that UK base
rates might have to be pushed up sharply to protect the pound.
A slide in share prices gathered pace towards the close and the FT-SE Index
ended 52 points down as the market resounded with suggestions that UK rates
could be forced higher by two percentage points without waiting for the
Maastricht referendum in France this weekend.
City analysts at the leading securities firms were summoned to meetings
after trading hours last night. Nerves came in for further testing following
reports that Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, had cancelled plans to
return to the Continental holiday interrupted by the Bundesbank's actions
last weekend; and also after unconfirmed rumours of crisis meetings at
either the Bank of England or at Downing Street.
The day's loss of 52.1 on the Footsie wiped out Monday's gain and left the
index at 2,370 last night. The big institutions, having taken the
opportunity to sell into a firm market on Monday, appeared to be less active
yesterday. Seaq volume, which increased towards the end of the session when
sterling was challenging its ERM low and the Bank of England was believed to
be supporting the UK currency, totalled 507.3m shares. Monday's Seaq
turnover of 537.9m shares reflected retail business worth Pounds 971.7m,
still on the low side.
With City analysts and the investment press taking a negative view of the
likely effects of the Bundesbank's rates cut, the UK stock market made a
gloomy start to the day. 'The writing was on the wall as soon as we saw the
Footsie open six points off after Wall Street had climbed 70 points
overnight,' commented one leading dealer.
The Footsie 2,400 mark melted away and occasional pauses to test support
levels invariably crumbled in the face of the market's negative sentiment.
Widespread falls in government bonds and persistent pressure on stock index
futures left equities to close virtually at their lowest levels of the day.
Nomura's Nicholas Knight, the spokesman for the bears, described the
Bundesbank's actions as no more than an anaesthetic for the financial
markets. 'The anaesthetic will wear off,' he warned clients yesterday
morning.
The fear that UK interest rates would be forced higher outweighed other
considerations, including Wall Street's overnight strength and even the
suggestion of a sterling devaluation, which also circulated in the financial
markets.
Building and construction shares, the chief casualties from high base rates,
lost more than the cautious gains achieved on Monday.
The international stocks brushed aside Wall Street's Monday upsurge, which
was reversed early in the new session when the Dow slipped 29 points. BAT
Industries, Glaxo and Wellcome were cut back as investors in the London
market dived for cover.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
