<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / BHP takes control of Foster's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BHP, Australia's biggest company, is taking effective control of Foster's
Brewing, the troubled Australian-based international brewer, in a deal worth
about ADollars 1.5bn (Pounds 540m).
BHP announced yesterday it was buying 32 per cent of Foster's, plus options,
from the receivers of International Brewing Holdings (IBH), the private
group controlled by Mr John Elliott, the former Foster's chief.
BHP has also offered to buy a further 5 per cent of Foster's capital from
Citibank, which has also placed part of IBH in receivership.
BHP underlined its influence by placing its nominees in four out of the 12
seats on the Foster's board, following Monday's resignation of Mr Elliott
and his associate, Mr Ken Biggins. BHP's move came as Foster's announced it
had plunged to net losses of ADollars 950.8m for the year to June and a
two-for-five rights issue to raise ADollars 1bn.
The losses followed asset write-downs of ADollars 1.19bn which disguised a
strong performance from the company's breweries, particularly in the UK.
BHP's ascendancy at Foster's has been expected since June 2 when it sent
receivers into the IBH group.
Mr John Prescott, BHP managing director, said last night his company was
comfortable with a long-term Foster's investment. BHP's exposure to Foster's
stands at just under ADollars 2.5bn or just over 10 per cent of the brewer's
total assets.
The receivers of IBH had been attempting to find alternative buyers for the
company's Foster's stake since mid-August after BHP made an offer for the
parcel, worth ADollars 2.39 a share.
That price, which involves debt forgiveness, equates to a cash price of
about ADollars 2 a share. It is higher than the ADollars 1.10-a-share price
on the Foster's scrip issue announced yesterday.
The issue will be fully underwritten by Potter Warburg, the Australian
investment bank. BHP says it will take up its entitlement and act as a
sub-underwriter.
Foster's shares fell 13 cents yesterday to a year low of ADollars 1.46 on
the Australian stock exchanges.
It said it expected dividends would total 6 cents a share out of profits
earned in the year to June 30 1993.
Results, Page 28
</TEXT>
