<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Scottish banking group rescued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN emergency rescue of a small Scottish private banking group, Adam &amp;
Company, has been organised over the past three weeks after it lost Pounds
21m on foreign currency futures.
The losses were made by the three employees of Adam's London treasury
dealing department, which trades in foreign currency and short-term
securities.
All three have been suspended pending the outcome of an investigation by a
firm of accountants, Price Waterhouse. Mr James Laurenson, Adam's managing
director, said the dealings had been 'unauthorised'. He said the treasury
team began to make the loss-making deals in April, but that senior
management only became aware of them three weeks ago.
He said the deals came to light because losses on them had become so big
that 'they could not be hidden'. All the dealing positions have now been
closed. However, the bank's capital - which was Pounds 7.1m at the end of
June - was wiped out by the losses. But the bank has been able to keep
trading because it has persuaded one of its shareholders to inject Pounds
21m of new capital into it.
The shareholder, which is buying Pounds 21m of new preference shares in
Adam's banking subsidiary, has asked for its identity to remain secret. The
preference shares pay no coupon for 10 years.
Mr Laurenson said the bank was 'incredibly' fortunate to have such a
supportive shareholder. He believes the bank has emerged stronger than
before, because of the terms of the injection and because of support by the
Royal Bank of Scotland, which has provided committed credit lines to the
bank.
Adam's biggest shareholders include the wealthy Schlumberger family and also
Standard Life, the Scottish insurance company. It is understood neither made
the capital injection.
Adam disclosed yesterday it had incurred a pre-tax loss of Pounds 5m in the
year to June 30, compared with a profit in the previous year of Pounds
869,000. The results included Pounds 6.58m of the Pounds 21m foreign
currency loss. Adam believes only Pounds 6.58m had in fact been incurred by
June 30.
Mr Laurenson said that without the foreign currency loss 'profits would have
almost doubled'.
</TEXT>
