<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Company reports on 'green' action urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES should be required to publish details of their environmental
policies and their performance in meeting 'green' objectives, a group of
accountants and industrialists said yesterday.
A report published by the environment research group of the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales says the Stock Exchange and the
Financial Reporting Council should consider formally encouraging companies
to provide environmental information.
It says any environmental factors affecting a company's policy and
activities, or having a financial impact, should be regularly accounted for.
The report does not reflect the official policy of the institute but Mr Ian
Plaistowe, its president, says in a foreword he will ask that its governing
council consider the proposals and make recommendations.
The research group includes the corporate chief economist at Imperial
Chemical Industries, the government's assistant auditor-general, and several
business and academic accountants.
The report says that as part of the annual reporting cycle a company should
publish details such as the nature and amount of expenditure on
environmental objectives, and the name of the director responsible for
environmental activities.
It says the Accounting Standards Board should consider a financial reporting
standard on environmental issues, and the Auditing Practices Board should
discuss producing guidelines on environmental audits.
Business Accountancy and the Environment. Technical Dept, ICAEW, Moorgate
Place, London EC2P 2BJ. Pounds 21.
