<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Producer prices almost static
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CORE INFLATION, as mea-sured by the producer prices index, continued its
down-ward path in the year to August as difficult domestic and overseas
conditions deterred UK manufacturers from raising prices.
Figures from the Central Statistical Office yesterday showed that the prices
of manufactured goods leaving factories scarcely moved last month, rising
just 0.1 per cent from the previous month.
That gave a year-on-year increase of 3.3 per cent, the lowest annual rate of
increase for more than 24 years. It compared with a rise of 3.4 per cent in
the year to July.
The annual rate of producer price inflation has been falling more or less
continuously since April last year, when it was 6.2 per cent.
Stripping out volatile food, drink and tobacco prices, the output prices
index rose 2.6 per cent in the year to August, the same as the annual rate
in May, which was the lowest since 1969. That compares with a high of 6.4
per cent in February last year.
The data suggest many manufacturers are continuing to cut prices to maintain
sales in a fragile climate of weak demand while benefiting from lower raw
material and wage costs.
The prices of raw materials and fuel used by manufacturing industry fell 2.2
per cent last month, reflecting weak demand for many types of commodities.
The CSO said prices paid for food manufacturing raw materials had fallen
particularly sharply.
The month-on-month drop compared with a fall of 0.2 per cent in July. It
brought the annual rate of decline for input prices to 1.9 per cent.
Seasonally adjusted, the prices of raw materials fell 1.9 per cent from the
previous month, the sharpest monthly fall since 1968.
The official figures underlined the favourable outlook for inflation in the
UK. The Treasury said lower producer inflation would feed through to further
reductions in retail price inflation.
</TEXT>
