<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a large amount of drama tonight, most of it clashing as usual. The
2-hour Inspector Morse on Channel 4 (8.30) shown previously on ITV, is, once
again, set in Oxford, this time in the university. Morse is called in when
an environmentalist is murdered just before he is due to give a lecture. The
fashionable subject of child abuse is well to the fore.
The even more trendy subject of transvestism is at the heart of BBC2's
'ScreenPlay', A Little Bit Of Lippy (9.00). When Marian finds women's
knickers in husband Rick's laundry she goes back to mum, only to discover
that there is no other woman but that Rick likes wearing the underwear
himself. Obsession (10.40 ITV) is a 1976 Hitchcock-type movie about a man
who meets the double of his dead wife. But a lot of people will be watching
BBC1's Inside Story (10.00) about today's white slave trade. Thousands of
women from poor countries are lured into the stripping and prostitution
business. Using hidden cameras it follows the trade from the Caribbean to
sex syndicates in Europe run by a 'Dutch based' gang who work the women for
as much as 15 hours a day.
