<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / National commercial radio launch delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RADIO Authority, the regulatory body for commercial radio, has decided
to postpone the launch of Britain's third national commercial radio station
until the spring of 1995.
According to Lord Chalfont, the authority chairman, the delay is partly
because of the recession but mainly to allow 'a kind of orderly progress in
the development of the radio regime.'
A spring 1995 launch will be about a year later than would be possible if
the franchise - INR 3 - was advertised and licensed as quickly as possible.
Mr Stuart Francis, chairman of the Association of Independent Radio
Companies, yesterday attacked the Radio Authority decision to delay the
launch of INR3 as 'sad and disappointing.'
Mr Francis said the original hope was to use the launch of three national
commercial stations to raise the profile of commercial radio and increase
its share of national advertising revenue from its present 2 per cent.
The decision means the BBC's 24-hour news station planned for 1994 will be
on the air before the third independent national station joins Classic FM
and Independent Music Radio, the pop music station.
The Radio Authority said it was going ahead with advertising five new
regional licences covering an audience of about 12m.
There would also be two new licences for the Greater London area and other
licences in Manchester, Birmingham and Wolverhampton.
Mr Francis said his association had wanted the national stations in place
before the regional companies were launched. 'If you have a plan you should
stick to it,' he said.
The regional stations covering areas such as Central Scotland, the
north-west and the west Midlands will compete with existing local stations.
Mr Francis said: 'The national stations offer a chance of attracting genuine
new money to radio.'
The Radio Authority was influenced in its decision by market research
suggesting it would take time for commercial radio to increase its slice of
overall advertising revenue significantly.
Lord Chalfont said one company could apply for and run all five regional
stations and even employ a similar format for each, but such an operator
could not also run a Greater London station, since this would amount to a
national network by the back door.
The Radio Authority also confirmed plans to re-advertise 130 existing
commercial radio licences over the next three years, starting next month
with Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
