<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Actuaries agree heavy cuts in policy bonuses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUBSTANTIALLY smaller bonuses will be paid in future on millions of
with-profits life assurance and pension policies, actuaries meeting at
Harrogate agreed yesterday.
Many life companies are anxious about the impact of lower bonuses - caused
by poor investment results in the past five years - on the public and on
intermediaries such as brokers and salesmen.
Some cuts were made last year but many offices maintained their bonuses in
the vain hope that investment conditions would improve.
Yesterday Mr John Martin, president of the Institute of Actuaries, chaired
an unprecedented meeting following the profession's annual conference.
Speakers stressed the fundamental structural changes on the investment
markets following the entry of the UK into the European Exchange Rate
Mechanism. It was not a question of once-and-for-all cuts, speakers
stressed. Reductions would continue for some years unless conditions were to
change.
The meeting was concerned about how to present the message to the public,
and some actuaries said they feared a struggle with life company boards over
setting a responsible bonus strategy.
One speaker called on appointed actuaries - the company officials who have a
statutory responsibility to safeguard the solvency of their life offices in
spite of competitive pressures to pay high bonuses - to 'stand up and make
sure that their views are heard. Marketing considerations must take second
place.'
Appointed actuaries also have a duty to consider policyholders' 'reasonable
expectations'. Speakers said those expectations had to be reduced.
'We have to get out and explain that something fundamental is happening
here,' one actuary said.
Support was offered for company actuaries whose views were ignored. 'Anyone
who is getting into a difficult situation and would welcome confidential
discussions with senior members of the profession is very much encouraged to
get in touch,' said a senior actuary.
Mr Martin said: 'This is a very important actuarial matter indeed. Bonuses
should be coming down. The debate is about when and how.'
</TEXT>
