FT  16 SEP 92 / Tecs seek earlier training for jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAINING and Enterprise Councils are seeking cuts in the amount of time
unemployed adults must wait before qualifying for training and job-search
opportunities.
The 82 Tecs, which administer publicly-funded training programmes in England
and Wales, propose provisions such as a Jobclub for the unemployed starting
in the first weeks of unemployment building up to entitlement to a broad
range of services at 13 weeks' unemployment. At present such services are
concentrated on people unemployed for more than six months.
Tecs have told the government the plan could lead to a sharp increase in the
number of jobs offered to the unemployed, but would not require more
government funds.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, is reviewing publicly funded
provision for the adult unemployed.
Tecs would also like the funding arrangements for Employment Training, the
main training scheme for the adult long-term unemployed, changed so that
individuals received pay instead of benefits. Tecs believe this would
improve the image of ET.
Tecs also ask for clearer lines of responsibility between them and the
government's Employment Service, which at present provides services such as
Jobclubs. Tecs would like to provide some of the services.
