<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Stock option schemes queried
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S largest shareholder group yesterday proposed guidelines on the
awarding of stock options for top executives which could severely limit
their use by large companies.
The National Association of Pension Funds, whose members manage over Pounds
250bn in pension fund assets, issued a consultation document in which it
proposed that shareholders ask companies to abandon the normal practice of
allowing top management to exercise stock options if a certain level of
earnings per share growth was achieved. Instead, the NAPF proposed that
options should only be exercisable if the share price outperformed an agreed
benchmark such as the FTA All-Share Index.
Because only half of companies in the index can outperform it, the
guidelines, if adopted, could severely curtail the issuance of executive
stock options.
The NAPF also said that, while it believes share option schemes have their
role in motivating top executives, profit-related pay and well structured
cash bonus schemes achieve that goal better.
'There is no evidence that share schemes encourage people to stay with their
shares longer than is appropriate,' said Mr Angus Matheson, chairman of the
NAPF's investment committee. The anecdotal evidence suggests that most
executives exercise their options and sell the shares as soon as the price
rises to the point at which a reasonable profit can be made. Thus, they do
not encourage managers to take a long-term view on a company's performance.
In explaining the NAPF's position, Mr Matheson said the review of stock
options began following general concern among the membership about whether
earnings per share are a reliable indicator of corporate performance.
'Everyone has become increasingly concerned about the validity of earnings
per share,' he said.
Fears that accounting conventions allow managements to distort EPS have led
shareholders to question it is a satisfactory basis for awarding
performance-related pay.
The NAPF proposed guidelines would assign a specific role to non-executive
directors who would have to confirm that, as well as the share price having
met a pre-determined benchmark, a sustained improvement in financial
performance had been achieved.
The NAPF position is not shared by Britain's other major shareholders'
group, the Association of British Insurers. While the ABI says it believes
real financial growth must be demonstrated, it sees no better measure than
EPS. Mr Matheson said 'protracted' discussions had been held with the ABI in
order to prevent the two shareholder groups from recommending different
policies to boards.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-2845</DOCNO>
