<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Bundesbank chief in row over need for realignment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German Bundesbank was last night at the centre of a renewed controversy
after reports that Mr Helmut Schlesinger, its president, had suggested that
a more comprehensive realignment of European currencies could have reduced
turbulence in currency markets.
The reports, quoted by DPA and VWD, the main German political and economic
news agencies, were denied last night by a spokesman for the German central
bank.
The reported comments were based on an interview given by Mr Schlesinger to
Handelsblatt, the German business newspaper, and to the Wall Street Journal.
They prompted hurried telephone calls to Germany from officials at the
Treasury and the Bank of England last night to seek clarification.
According to the news agencies, Mr Schlesinger said that the measures taken
so far had not resolved all the problems in the markets.
The Bundesbank chief was reported to have suggested that the weekend
realignment of the Italian lira had not gone far enough and that a wider
realignment could have been more effective in reducing tensions in the
currency market. He did not rule out continuing pressure on individual
currencies.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said last night: 'There has never been any
question of sterling being realigned or devalued and at no stage did anybody
else suggest we should move with the Italians.'
For its part, the Bundesbank said through a spokesman after consulting Mr
Schlesinger: 'This statement is no authorised version of the interview.'
It added: 'The president did not say it in that way or mean it in that way.
The words were suggested to him and he did not answer them.' The spokesman
said an authorised version of the interview would appear in the Wall Street
Journal.
Mr Hans Mundorf, editor-in-chief of Handelsblatt said last night: 'This
interview . . . was conducted by the head of our currencies and capital
markets staff. I have no doubt in the correctness of the information he gave
to DPA.'
The reported statements are in line with what is seen as a common Bundesbank
view, but one it has been careful never to express publicly.
Few officials in Bonn deny that there had been arguments in the Bundesbank
for a wider realignment as part of last weekend's changes, but they insist
that the 'political reality' only allowed a limited move involving the lira.
The officials say that devaluation of sterling was 'not really considered as
a valid option' because of the fierce hostility of the British government.
According to the excerpts of the interview on German news agencies, Mr
Schlesinger said the EMS was now considerably more relaxed than it had been
last week.
The Bundesbank chief was said to have noted that other currencies could be
hit ahead of France's Sunday vote on the Maastricht Treaties.
But the report continued: 'Even if France were to vote to reject the
treaties - which he (Mr Schlesinger) thought unlikely - other currencies
such as the pound sterling were not likely to come under similar pressure to
that placed on the lira.'
</TEXT>
