<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / PM cancels Seville trip to deal with 'business'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday cancelled an official visit to Spain, 24 hours
before he was due to fly out, in a move which heightened nervousness in the
City and at Westminster over the depth of the government's economic
difficulties.
The prime minister's unusual step put further pressure on the pound, which
fell to a new low in the exchange rate mechanism, at one point dropping to
within a tenth of a pfennig of its floor.
It also provoked fresh speculation at Westminster that the government has
serious problems in reaching agreement on the 1993-94 public expenditure
round, due to be discussed by the newly formed chancellor's committee on
Thursday.
Downing Street insisted that the eleventh-hour decision to postpone Mr
Major's visit to Seville's Expo 92 exhibition had nothing to do with
sterling but was to meet the pressure of business on his diary.
Officials said the new system for managing public expenditure was 'new
territory' for the government which warranted close attention from the prime
minister.
They also added that he would be using the empty space in his diary to
examine the spending implications of the new Council Tax and plans for the
new BBC Charter.
The explanations were widely greeted with scepticism. One Tory MP, Mr
Richard Shepherd, warned that the impression was that the government was
'losing control of the economy.'
Labour seized on the cancellation as a tacit admission by the government of
the dire state of the economy.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said: 'It is a sign that they have
been driven to accept, as we have been urging on them for many, many weeks,
that this situation is extremely serious.'
Independent observers suggested Mr Major may have calculated that it was
better to risk market unease at the cancellation of the trip than to be
absent abroad when the economy was under intense pressure.
With the Treasury continuing to insist that the government will use any
means necessary to maintain sterling's ERM position, an interest rate rise
cannot be ruled out.
Some MPs recall the humiliation for the Labour government in 1976 when Mr
Denis (now Lord) Healey, the chancellor, was forced to return from Heathrow
to tackle an economic crisis.
No way out from tough decisions, Page 20
</TEXT>
