<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / City set to defend exchange markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING City institutions were yesterday considering making a forthright
statement in defence of unrestricted foreign exchange markets, because of
concerns that the markets and dealers are being blamed for the inability of
the UK government to reduce interest rates.
The Bank of England has been approached to join with the Corporation of
London and leading banks in making a public statement that unrestricted
flows of capital in foreign exchange markets are positive for the economy.
'Politicians are representing the free markets as a bad thing', said an
executive involved in the discussions. 'We fear that the general public
blames the City for the country's economic problems.'
The mood among City dealers and executives over the past few weeks of sharp
fluctuations in currency markets - prompting huge rises in interest rates in
Italy and Sweden - has become very defensive.
There are widespread fears that the exchange volatility and the government's
inability to cut interest rates could lead to pressure for new regulations
to be introduced into foreign exchange markets.
City institutions want to make it clear that it is not their fault that
sterling is under pressure. However, they are unclear how to say this
without putting the blame on the government by implication, which they are
reluctant to do.
The Bank of England has not decided whether it will get involved in making
any such statement in defence of free markets.
City institutions are also organising a related campaign to reassert the
strength of Europe's financial markets. They fear that international
financial institutions may reduce their investments in Europe if the French
vote against the Maastricht agreement on Sunday.
The Corporation of London and UK banks are keen to stress that the City will
remain one of the world's three most important financial centres, whatever
the outcome of the vote.
In order to reinforce this confidence, they will be lobbying hard at the
annual International Monetary Fund meeting in Washington next week.
Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, the governor of the Bank of England, is likely to
be involved in this lobbying.
If the French vote in favour of Maastricht, part of this IMF-week campaign
will concentrate on the need for any future European Central Bank to be
based in London.
</TEXT>
