<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 92 / Hazards of reporting figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Commentating on the Singapore economy can be a hazardous business, writes
Kieran Cooke.
In late June, the Singapore newspaper Business Times published preliminary
government figures for GDP growth in the second quarter of the year. The
figures gave a lower than expected growth of 4.6-4.8 per cent.
Six weeks later, officers from Singapore's Internal Security Department
(ISD) questioned Business Times journalists and took away notebooks and
computer files. The preliminary figures were apparently based on leaked
information.
According to the Ministry of Home Affairs, the ISD officers were carrying
out their investigations in accordance with Singapore's Official Secrets
Act. Under the act, anyone who obtains such information and uses it 'in any
manner prejudicial to the safety or interests of Singapore' can be jailed
for up to two years.
Civil servants have been questioned, as have representatives of foreign
investment houses, about the source of the figures.
</TEXT>
